</description><pubDate>Fri, 24 Jan 2014 15:26:40 -0800</pubDate><guid>http://www.spokesman.com/blogs/tech-deck/2014/jan/24/test-driving-tesla-model-s/</guid></item><item><title>Every NES start screen. All of them.</title><link>http://www.spokesman.com/blogs/tech-deck/2014/jan/22/every-nes-start-screen-ever-like-seriously-all-of-them-for-hours/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;I saw this on &lt;a href="http://www.wired.com/gamelife/2014/01/nes-title-screens/"&gt;Wired&lt;/a&gt; and had to share it here. YouTube user &lt;span class="qualified-channel-title ellipsized"&gt;&lt;span class="qualified-channel-title-wrapper"&gt;&lt;span class="qualified-channel-title-text" dir="ltr"&gt;&lt;a class="spf-link branded-page-header-title-link" dir="ltr" href="http://www.youtube.com/user/NicksplosionFX" title="NicksplosionFX"&gt;NicksplosionFX &lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;compiled a video made up of every NES/Famicom start screen ever made. No big deal, right?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It&amp;#39;s 2 hours, 50 minutes and 12 seconds long.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;THAT&amp;#39;s *kinda* a big deal. Can&amp;#39;t even imagine the insane amount of time it must have taken to find all the ROMs, load them into an emulator, screen cap the title screen, rinse lather repeat, then edit it all together.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You sir, are both a gentleman and a scholar.&lt;/p&gt;

